Phishing 
[Internal Justification/Use Case] We have observed activity/detections associated with phishing. 


Phishing
Customer Recommendation Action:

Bitdefender MDR analysts have identified potential phishing within the environment. 

[Host(s)/User(s)/Email(s)]

[URLs/Attachments]

Analysts recommend taking the following initial steps to investigate and remediate the phishing attempt.

Search across all emails for the sender, subject, links or attachments associated with the phishing email.

Purge the emails identified from the email servers.

Block the associated links or attachments within email filtering, networking, or endpoint tools.

Reset passwords for accounts targeted, and replace them with long passphrases formed by a combination of unrelated words.

After these steps are completed, analysts recommend following these best practices to reduce the risk of future phishing or social engineering attempts.  

Ensure all devices are monitored by Bitdefender MDR.

Enable two-factor authentication (2FA): Two-factor authentication adds an additional layer of security by requiring a second form of verification, such as a text message or authenticator app, along with the password. This can help protect against unauthorized access even if the password is compromised. The 2FA codes should never be shared with anyone. 

Be cautious with emails: Do not open emails or click on links or download attachments from unknown or suspicious sources. Verify the authenticity of emails, especially those requesting sensitive information or urging for immediate action.

Check URLs and domain names: Be wary of URLs or domain names that are misspelled or look suspicious. Always verify the legitimacy of the website or domain before providing any personal or sensitive information.

Be cautious with personal information: Do not provide personal or sensitive information, such as usernames, passwords, or financial details, in response to unsolicited emails or messages. Always verify the authenticity of the request through a trusted channel before sharing any sensitive information.

Use spam filters: Implement spam filters in email systems to automatically filter out known phishing emails and malicious content.

Customer Recommendation Reason: 

Phishing and social engineering attacks can lead to the compromise of sensitive information or unauthorized actions by tricking users into revealing confidential data or performing actions that may compromise security. Prompt investigation and appropriate actions can help mitigate the risk of further incidents and safeguard the security and integrity of systems and data.

