After these steps are completed, analysts recommend following these best practices to reduce the risk of future spam attempts.  

Ensure all devices are monitored by Bitdefender MDR.

Enable two-factor authentication (2FA): Two-factor authentication adds an additional layer of security by requiring a second form of verification, such as a text message or authenticator app, along with the password. This can help protect against unauthorized access even if the password is compromised. The 2FA codes should never be shared with anyone. 

Be cautious with emails: Do not open emails or click on links or download attachments from unknown or suspicious sources. Verify the authenticity of emails, especially those requesting sensitive information or urging for immediate action.

Check URLs and domain names: Be wary of URLs or domain names that are misspelled or look suspicious. Always verify the legitimacy of the website or domain before providing any personal or sensitive information.

Be cautious with personal information: Do not provide personal or sensitive information, such as usernames, passwords, or financial details, in response to unsolicited emails or messages. Always verify the authenticity of the request through a trusted channel before sharing any sensitive information.

Use spam filters: Implement spam filters in email systems to automatically filter out known spam emails and malicious content.

Customer Recommendation Reason: 

Spam email attacks can lead to the compromise of sensitive information or unauthorized actions by tricking users into revealing confidential data or performing actions that may compromise security. Prompt investigation and appropriate actions can help mitigate the risk of further incidents and safeguard the security and integrity of systems and data.

Removable Media

Removable Media
Customer Recommendation Action: 

Analysts recommend using only trusted removable media devices, disabling "AutoRun" if enabled within your environment, and disabling the ability for hosts to execute commands through autorun.inf. Analysts recommend blocking External Storage devices under Device Control Rules on the associated policy for the host. Authorized devices can be whitelisted within the Device Control Exclusions.  

Customer Recommendation Reason: 

Removable media devices, such as flash drives and memory cards, can be used as a common vector for malware to spread across environments. Disabling "AutoRun" and preventing the execution of commands through autorun.inf can help mitigate the risk of malware propagation through removable media devices. Using only trusted removable media devices also reduces the likelihood of introducing potentially malicious software into your environment.

Manual Log Deletion Detections (e.g. WevtutilLogDeletion) 

Manual Log Deletion Detections (e.g. WevtutilLogDeletion) 
Customer Recommendation Action:

Bitdefender MDR recommends sending the <logs (e.g. Windows Event Logs)> on <host(s)> to a remote location and enabling log rollovers.

Customer Recommendation Reason:

Sending logs to a remote location avoids data allocation issues on the device and to ensure that logs are preserved for analysis. Instead of manually deleting logs, set up log rollover so that older logs are automatically archived or deleted when new logs are generated. This helps to ensure that logs are regularly maintained without triggering alerts for manual deletion.

